# ADR artifact — Architecture Decision Record.
# Usage: copy to docs/sdlc/adr/ADR-<n>.yaml. One per decision.
#
# The 3-question gating test (apply BEFORE writing an ADR):
#   1. Does this decision constrain future work in a non-trivial way?
#      (If no — it's an implementation detail, not an ADR.)
#   2. Is at least one credible alternative being rejected?
#      (If no — there is no decision to record.)
#   3. Will reversing this later be expensive?
#      (If no — capture as a code comment, not an ADR.)
# If the answer to any question is "no", DO NOT create this ADR.

id: ADR-001
title: Use TypeScript monorepo with pnpm workspaces
status: proposed                 # proposed | accepted | superseded | needs-revisit
decision: |                      # required, the choice in plain language
  Crux is structured as a TypeScript monorepo with pnpm workspaces; each package
  declared in pnpm-workspace.yaml has its own tsconfig extending tsconfig.base.json.
alternatives_considered:
  - option: single-package repo with deep src/ tree
    rationale: rejected — five distinct deliverables (core, adapter, cli, extension, audit-site)
      have different dependency surfaces and release cadences.
  - option: nx or turbo-orchestrated monorepo
    rationale: rejected at v1 — extra tooling burden without a current need for cached graph builds.
consequences:                    # what becomes easier and what becomes harder
  - Cross-package refactors stay atomic.
  - VS Code extension and Astro audit-site keep isolated dependency trees.
  - Contributors must learn pnpm workspace conventions.
resolves:                        # GRILL ids this decision answers
  - GRILL-002
satisfies:                       # REQ ids this decision serves
  - REQ-003
constrains:                      # MOD ids whose shape is now fixed by this decision
  - MOD-001
  - MOD-002
revisit_when: |                  # the trigger that would force a re-look
  Build orchestration becomes a measurable bottleneck OR a sixth deliverable joins the repo.
validated_by:                    # tasks / tests / metrics that prove the decision is in force
  - task: TASK-007
  - check: pnpm -r build succeeds in CI
